The Real Problem:
Android Emulator doesn't have direct HTTP access to your localhost server without proper configuration. The emulator runs in a virtualized environment with its own network stack.

The REAL Solution: ADB Reverse Proxy
The ONLY reliable way to make localhost:3002 work in Android emulator is:

Step 1: Check if ADB can see your emulator
bash
adb devices
Step 2: If no devices found, start your emulator properly
bash
# Find your emulator
emulator -list-avds

# Start your emulator (replace with your actual AVD name)
emulator -avd Medium_Phone_API_36.1
Step 3: Run ADB reverse command
bash
adb reverse tcp:3002 tcp:3002
Step 4: Verify it worked
bash
adb reverse --list
Should show: tcp:3002 tcp:3002

If ADB commands don't work:
Find your Android SDK path:
bash
flutter doctor -v
Use full path to ADB:
bash
# Example:
C:\Users\ratho\AppData\Local\Android\Sdk\platform-tools\adb.exe reverse tcp:3002 tcp:3002
Alternative: Use Chrome for Development
Since you can't get the emulator working, use Chrome:

bash
flutter run -d chrome
Simple Config That Will Work:
simple_config.dart
dart
class SimpleConfig {
  // For now, just use this simple config
  static const String baseUrl = 'http://localhost:3002';
  
  static const String getAllCoffees = '$baseUrl/coffees';
  static const String getCategories = '$baseUrl/categories';
  static const String cart = '$baseUrl/cart';
  // ... other endpoints
}
The Truth About Android Emulator Networking:
Android Emulator has its own virtual network

localhost in emulator â‰  localhost on your PC

10.0.2.2 only works in SOME emulator configurations

ADB reverse is the ONLY guaranteed solution

