Immediate Action:
Run your app in Chrome:

bash
flutter run -d chrome
This will at least prove your server and Flutter code are working correctly, while we figure out the emulator networking issue.

The problem is NOT your Flutter code - it's the Android emulator network configuration that's blocking the connection to your localhost server.

Perfect! The ADB reverse command worked (no error means success). Now let's verify and test:

Step 1: Check if the reverse proxy is active
bash
adb reverse --list
You should see:

text
tcp:3002 tcp:3002
Step 2: Test the connection in Android emulator
Open Chrome browser in your Android emulator

Visit: http://localhost:3002/coffees

You should see your JSON coffee data

Step 3: Test your Flutter app
Now run your Flutter app:

bash
flutter run
What ADB Reverse Does:
âœ… Creates a tunnel from Android's localhost:3002 to your PC's localhost:3002

âœ… Your Flutter code can keep using http://localhost:3002 (client requirement satisfied)

âœ… Actually connects to your Express.js server on your development machine
